{
  "texts": [
    "Next, we look at how the Manne program inuenced decisions in policy-relevant appellate cases.",
    "Using a sample of cases hand-coded for ideological direction (see, e.g., Haire et al. 2003) we nd that, post Manne attendance, judges vote for conservative verdicts in economics-relevant cases (but not in non-economics cases).",
    "Further, using a set of machine-coded decisions, we nd that Manne attendees subsequently are more likely to vote against regulatory agencies, in particular on the labor and environmental issues that early law and economics focused on.",
    "Using newly collected data on antitrust decisions, we also nd some evidence that post-Manne judges are more likely to vote against antitrust protections, although this result is more sensitive to specication than the others.",
    "Moving to the district courts, we analyze the impact on criminal sentencing (which is handled by district judges rather than appeals judges)."
  ]
}